Sediment accumulation rate is much higher above the Ambrosia rise, causing a major kink in the age-depth curve, and Bacon could not fit a reasonable age model if the surface age was included. name: Neotoma 1
notes:
Sediment accumulation rate is much higher above the Ambrosia rise, causing a major kink in the age-depth curve, and Bacon could not fit a reasonable age model if the surface age was included. Thus, for the Bacon age model, the top age was set to 90 cal BP at 1908 cm. The ages above 1908 cm were determined by linear interpolaton between the surface (1550 cm) and 1908 cm.

name: Herring & Gavin 2015
notes: In original publication for Star Meadows, authors did not make an age model below 14C dateable ages (250 cm), but did argue that events in core correlated to MIS. Clam model was computed for the whole core based on these correlations.  Note substantial uncertainties prior to radiocarbon window.This age model based on a modified version of CLAM (Gavin) that uses a monotonic spline or a stineman spline.

name: Friel et al. 2014
notes:
Based on IntCal09 calibration curve. A hiatus exists at 55 cm. Because a section of the core between ~7 and 19 cm depth had nearly constant 210Pb activity, this section was removed and ages are based on a linear regression model for the section of the core whre 210Pb decays regularly (24-52 cm) and used to estimate 'normal' accumulation rate (see Friel 2014).

Ages were calculated every 1 [every] cm [depth], from 0 [dmin] to 251 [dmax] cm

Dates assumed outlying [outliers]: 18 (beta.325704) 
A hiatus was inferred at 55.5 cm [hiatus]

name: NAPD 1
notes: Chron uses 11 radiocarbon dates plus the top (-25 BP, 650 cm). Five levels above the Ambrosia-rise (662-702 cm) have been corrected for compaction (see Grimm 1981). Because the radiocarbon date at the Ambrosia-rise (630±55) is ca. 530 years too old and because a hardwater effect is expected, all radiocarbon dates except the basal date have been corrected for a 530 yr reservoir. The basal date on wood in the trash layer should not be subject to hardwater error and was not corrected. The base of the lake sediment was assigned an age 60 years younger than the trash layer.

Bacon settings file:
0 #d.min
380 #d.max
1 #d.by
1 #depths.file
NA #slump
1 20 #acc.mean
1.5 1.5 #acc.shape
0.7 #mem.mean
4 #mem.strength
100 #hiatus.depths
2 #hiatus.mean
1 #hiatus.shape
0 #BCAD
1 #cc
0 #postbomb
IntCal13 #cc1
Marine13 #cc2
SHCal13 #cc3
ConstCal #cc4
cm #unit
0 #normal
3 #t.a
4 #t.b
0 #d.R
0 #d.STD
0.95 #prob
